{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6037b928-0102-4ea4-9ed7-4b9b2f9a82ea","content":"## What happened\n\n`DSA` has been obsolete since `SYSLIB0030` was introduced. .NET on macOS never used Apple's frameworks for DSA — it relied on an OpenSSL shim. In **.NET 11**, that shim-based DSA support on macOS was **removed**, so `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS. Linux (OpenSSL-native) and Windows (CNG) still work.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nYou have two options:\n\n### Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended for legacy verification)\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\npublic static bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] data, byte[] signature,\n                                       DsaPublicKeyParameters publicKey)\n{\n    ISigner signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\");\n    signer.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);\n    signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\n    return signer.VerifySignature(signature);\n}\n```\n\nThis is cross-platform and doesn't depend on OS-level DSA support.\n\n### Option 2 — Migrate to a modern algorithm\n\nIf you control both signing and verification, migrate to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519**, which are supported on all platforms:\n\n```csharp\nusing var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create(ECCurve.NamedCurves.nistP256);\n```\n\n**Recommendation:** If you must verify *existing* legacy DSA signatures, go with BouncyCastle. If you can re-sign, migrate to ECDSA/Ed25519 and stop suppressing `SYSLIB0030`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a2377a5b-462d-4a4c-84f0-92c36f79cab1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason through this based on my knowledge of .NET's cryptography changes.\n\nThis is a known breaking change in .NET. Let me explain what happened:\n\nStarting with .NET 7+, Microsoft has been progressively removing support for older/weaker cryptographic algorithms. DSA (the original DSA, not ECDSA) has been deprecated and its support has been removed on certain platforms.\n\nSpecifically, in .NET 7, `DSA.Create()` started throwing `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS because Apple's Security framework (and CommonCrypto/CryptoKit) dropped support for DSA. On Linux, DSA still works through OpenSSL, and on Windows it works through CNG/CAPI.\n\n\nThe timeline here is important—.NET 10 released in November 2025, and .NET 11 is coming in November 2026. The DSA obsolescence has been a gradual process, with the `SYSLIB0030` warning introduced to mark DSA as obsolete in earlier versions. On Apple platforms specifically, the support has been progressively tightened as the framework moved away from deprecated cryptographic standards.\n\nSo in this .NET 11 scenario, the most likely explanation is that DSA support was finally removed on macOS entirely—either throwing a `PlatformNotSupportedException` or dropping the OpenSSL fallback that previously allowed it to work. Apple's security frameworks have never properly supported DSA, and .NET finally enforced that limitation. If you need to handle legacy DSA signatures, you'd need to turn to a cross-platform library like BouncyCastle... A has been progressively deprecated with SYSLIB0030 marking it as obsolete, and eventually `DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on browsers and macOS. Since this is a .NET 10 to 11 upgrade scenario, I should explain the likely breaking change and provide practical guidance without needing external resources.","outputTokens":1368,"requestId":"3012:B9052:15E8BA3:18AEA60:6A067B52"},"id":"73a2400e-4c8d-434d-b2c7-93c9e60b4bb7","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:48:32.577Z","parentId":"a478cc0e-eae0-481e-8087-3c52144f04b6"}
